### 2. Use the PC-algorithm on the data your received to ‘discover’ the structure of the causal system. Exclude the dichotomized cause variable from this analysis.<br><br>

First we load the data: 

```{r}
load("Kanga.Rdata")
summary(df)
```

Then we use the pc-algorithm

```{r}
# Excluding the dichotomized cause variable
df2 <- df %>%
  dplyr::select(-BC_dich)

# Define the structure of the data for the PC-algorithm
suffStat <- list(C = cor(df2), # Inter-variable correlations  
                 n = nrow(df2))

# Fit the PC-algorithm
pc_fit <- pc(suffStat = suffStat, 
             indepTest = gaussCItest, 
             p = ncol(df2), 
             alpha = 0.01)

# Plot the CP-DAG inferred from the PC-algorithm
plot(pc_fit, 
     main = "Inferred CPDAG using pcalg", 
     labels = colnames(df2))
```

**a) Provide the CP-DAG. Discuss the main findings, e.g.: How many equivalent DAGs are there? Are there paths for which you know/do not know the direction? Are the results sensible/surprising given your common sense of the substantive topic (you are allowed but not required to back your ideas up with literature)?**

```{r}

# Extract the adjacency matrix of the cpdag from pc_fit1
cpdag_mat <- as(pc_fit,"matrix")

# Each row is a DAG adjacency matrix in vector form (by rows)
res1 <- pdag2allDags(cpdag_mat)

# We can get the adjacency matrix of an individual DAG using
res1_dags <- list()
for(i in 1:nrow(res1$dags)){
  res1_dags[[i]] <- t(matrix(res1$dags[i,],6,6,byrow = TRUE))
}
# Notice we have to transpose the adjacency matrix here for qgraph!

# We can plot each of these just as we did above
par(mfrow = c(1,3))
for(i in 1:3){
  qgraph(res1_dags[[i]], directed = TRUE, asize = 8, vsize = 15,  labels = colnames(df2))
}
```

There are three equivalent DAGs based on the CP-DAG that was inferred with the pc-algorithm. In these DAGs the paths between agressive behaviour (AB), body condition (BC) and testosterone levels (TL) could be directed in different ways, while the conditional independencies remain the same. In all cases, reproductive success (RS) is caused by body size (BS) and dominance status (DS), which is caused by agressive behaviour (AB) and body condition (BC). In general these causal structures make sense, although the direct connection between BS and RS was a bit surprising.

**b. Select and provide the DAG you think is best from the equivalence set, that is, that you feel is most realistic/sensible given the information you received on the variables/overall context. Why do you prefer this DAG? Are there things about it that you find unrealistic?**

From the three equivalent DAGs the first one makes most sense, where:

* BC -> TL
* TL -> AB 

It does not seem likely that agressive behaviour causes higher testosterone levels, so it can't be the third one. Also, it is more likely that body condition influences testosterone levels, as better nutritional status and energy reserves can probably increase hormone production, while testosterone alone may not directly improve body condition. Moreover, BC also includes the age of the kangaroos, and it is not possible that TL causes the age of the animals. So this is our final DAG:

```{r}
kang <- dagify(
  TL ~ BC,
  AB ~ TL,
  DS ~ AB + BC,
  RS ~ DS + BS,
  
  exposure = "BC", 
  outcome = "DS", 
  
   coords = list(
     x = c(
       BC = 1,
       TL = 0,
       DS = 0, 
       AB = -1,
       RS = 1, 
       BS = 2),
     y = c(
      BC = 0,
       TL = 0.5,
       DS = -0.5, 
       AB = 0,
       RS = -1, 
       BS = -0.5)) 
  
)

# Plot the DAG
ggdag_status(kang) + theme_dag()
```


