### 6. For the causal effect of question 3, based on your selected DAG, use either matching, inverse propensity weighting, or subclassification (your choice) to estimate the causal effect of your dichotomous cause variable on the outcome. Briefly discuss the steps you take and the results.

When we calculate the propensity score of a treatment variable (which is the basis of matching, IPW, and subclassification), we use all the confounders between the treatment and the outcome. The problem is that, as mentioned earlier, there are no confounders in our DAG.

We decided to perform inverse population weighting anyway to demonstrate it, using all the variables present in the DAG except the outcome. This is WRONG.

The first step is to calculate the propensity scores (i.e., the probability to be in the normal/good BC group (X=1) as opposed to the poor BC group (X=0)).

```{r}

# Run the logistic regression analysis
logreg <- glm(BC_dich ~ TL + AB + BS + BS + RS, 
                    family = binomial(), data = df)

# Obtain a prediction of the probability of treatment (i.e., DIET=1) 
ps <- predict(logreg, type = "response")

# Add this predicted probability to the datafile
df$ps <- ps

```

```{r}
# Load necessary libraries
library(survey)  
library(tableone)  

# Compute inverse probability weights (IPW) based on propensity scores (ps)
weight <- ifelse(df$BC_dich == 1, 1 / (df$ps), 1 / (1 - df$ps))

# Create a survey design object with the computed weights
weighteddata <- svydesign(ids = ~ 1, data = df, weights = ~ weight)

# Create an unweighted table summarizing variables across strata of BC_dich
table <- CreateTableOne(vars = c("TL", "AB", "BS", "RS"), strata = "BC_dich", 
                        data = df, test = FALSE)

# Create a weighted table using the IPW
weightedtable <- svyCreateTableOne(vars = c("TL", "AB", "BS", "RS"), strata = "BC_dich", 
                                   data = weighteddata, test = FALSE)

# Print the unweighted table with standardized mean differences (SMD)
print(table, smd = TRUE)

# Print the weighted table with standardized mean differences (SMD)
print(weightedtable, smd = TRUE)

```

This shows that in the pseudo-population created using IPW, the two groups no longer differ much on any of the covariates; for all of them, the standardized mean difference does not exceed the rule-of-thumb value of 0.1. This would imply that IPW is entirely successful in mimicking an RCT. (In reality it does not, because as said before, we are building the propensity scores on the wrong covariates.) Now, we proceed to calculate the average causal effect (ACE).

```{r}
model <- svyglm(DS ~ BC_dich, design = weighteddata)
summary(model)
confint(model)
```

The estimated ACE is 0.44, and it's significantly different from 0.

### 7. What is your overall conclusion about the causal effect based on your results/reflections  from steps 2-6? 

We have calculated three different ACE estimates: one using the prima facie approach, one based on a DAG-driven regression, and one using IPW. The first and second estimates coincide, as there are no confounders in the DAG. The third, however, is based on incorrect assumptions and was computed purely for demonstration purposes. Nonetheless, it is worth noting that its value is not too far from the prima facie estimate.

In conclusion, we can say that the ACE is equal to 0.34.

### 8. What do you take away about causal inference from this and the previous assignment (if anything)? The answer to this question will not be graded.

Honestly, these two assignments have made us question how well causal inference actually works. In particular, we have serious doubts about causal discovery and the PC algorithm. If it performs so poorly with generated data and a sample size of 500 — which is not small — we wonder how it could possibly perform well in real-world scenarios, especially when the number of variables increases.

That said, one positive takeaway is the importance of carefully selecting which variables to include in a model. The idea that the more, the better is not just ineffective but actually harmful. This was something we already knew, but taking this course has helped us truly understand why it matters so much.








